
  <sn><md>#### Indus Civilization

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
The civilization is known as the **Indus Civilization** because it developed along the banks of the `Indus River`. It is believed that the `Dravidian people` established this urban civilization around `3,500 years` ago.

`Harappa` (c. `2600–1900 BCE`) was a Bronze Age civilization. The two greatest cities of the Harappan Civilization were `Harappa` and `Mohenjo-daro`.

Harappa was built on the banks of the `Ravi River`, a tributary of the Indus. It is located in the `Punjab Province of present-day Pakistan`. Mohenjo-daro (meaning *"Mound of the Dead"*) was built on the banks of the Indus River.

This ancient civilization was first discovered in `1921` at `Harappa` in Punjab Province. In 1922, `Rakhaldas Bandyopadhyay` discovered the ruins of Mohenjo-daro in Larkana District of Sindh Province, Pakistan. During the excavations, various `Copper Age artifacts` were uncovered.
:::
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
![img](https://i.pinimg.com/originals/3e/40/89/3e4089efaad8ff49c03f3f68b041fa7f.jpg)
:::
:::

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
![img](https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn\:ANd9GcS2Jl5YV8ExbLsB6F62hSZKBbRVygDSpKjXeKznLNXtH-APcSfxprrVqqFh\&amp;s=10)
:::
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
Evidence suggests that the Indus Civilization possessed an `elite urban culture`. Both major cities had `well-planned drainage systems`. Along the streets stood `two- and three-story houses`. Each house contained a bathroom with a bathing area and a private well.

Seals made of bone and stone have been discovered in both Mohenjo-daro and Harappa. The `seals and pottery` found in the Indus Civilization show similarities to Mesopotamian artifacts. Most of the people of this civilization were engaged in agriculture.

One of the most significant contributions of this civilization was the development of a `system of measurement`. The inhabitants used standardized `weights` for measuring goods and various `scales` for measuring length.
:::
